if(!window.BOOKS) window.BOOKS={}; window.BOOKS['unholy-ground'] = {"id":"unholy-ground","title":"Unholy Ground","series":"Lyrian Chronicles 8","authors":{"campaign":"Leaflit","adapted":"Leaflit","edited":"Leaflit"},"description":"A replay novel based on events from an Angel\u0027s Sword TTRPG campaign. Kane, Kori Itia, and Hjerngan are sent on a dangerous mission to Westria to investigate a murdered spy and uncover a terrifying plot.","cast":[{"name":"Kori Itia","title":"The Amethyst Company Operative","player":"Oniichan","class":"Chronoblade"},{"name":"Kane","title":"The Stalwart Acolyte Knight","player":"Sabbrewolf","class":"Paladin"},{"name":"Hjerngan","title":"The Sylvan Swordsman","player":"Ayra","class":"Swordmaster"}],"pages":[{"title":"Title Page","type":"title","content":"<div class=\"title-page\"><h1>Unholy Ground</h1><h2>Lyrian Chronicles 8</h2><hr><p>Campaign By: Leaflit</p><p>Adapted By: Leaflit</p><p>Edited By: Leaflit</p><hr><p><em>This story is a replay novel. Everything occurred over a game of Angel\u0027s Sword TTRPG.</em></p><p><a href=\"https://www.angelssword.com\">https://www.angelssword.com</a></p></div>","chapter":1},{"title":"Cast","type":"cast","content":"<div class=\"cast-page\"><h2>Starring</h2><div class=\"cast-grid\"><div class=\"cast-card\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-kori.png\" class=\"cast-portrait\" alt=\"Kori Itia\"><div class=\"cast-info\"><h3>Kori Itia</h3><p class=\"cast-title\">The Amethyst Company Operative</p><div class=\"cast-meta\">Player: Oniichan | Class: Chronoblade</div></div></div><div class=\"cast-card\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-kane.png\" class=\"cast-portrait\" alt=\"Kane\"><div class=\"cast-info\"><h3>Kane</h3><p class=\"cast-title\">The Stalwart Acolyte Knight</p><div class=\"cast-meta\">Player: Sabbrewolf | Class: Paladin</div></div></div><div class=\"cast-card\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-kane.png\" class=\"cast-portrait\" alt=\"Hjerngan\"><div class=\"cast-info\"><h3>Hjerngan</h3><p class=\"cast-title\">The Sylvan Swordsman</p><div class=\"cast-meta\">Player: Ayra | Class: Swordmaster</div></div></div></div></div>","chapter":1},{"title":"The Mothergreen Conference","type":"story","content":"<h2>Episode 1 \u2014 The Beginning</h2><p>At a conference room in Mothergreen, the representatives of the four countries had gathered around a table. Representing Northi was Pandion, the newly promoted Major in the Northi Armed Forces and the primary attendee on behalf of Northi\u0027s military interests. Beside him was Shannon, the Head of Intelligence for Northi and its civilian interests, both of them present to discuss the critical matters at hand.</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-pandion.png\" alt=\"Pandion, the Northi Major\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Pandion, the Northi Major</p></div><p>On the opposite side, the Westrians had sent their Bishop to represent the Church\u0027s interests. Though formally a diplomatic figure, the Bishop\u0027s influence reached far beyond the pulpit.</p><p>The Easterner Delegation was composed of Aeriele, one of the leaders of Easter, representing the Fae and the interests of the Easter Accords.</p><p>Representing Kirara was a delegate cloaked in formality whose role was only to observe and report back to their government.</p><p>As the meeting commenced, the room was thick with tension, each participant aware of the unspoken power dynamics at play. The weight of decisions made here could easily shift the balance between the four nations.</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"The Missing Operative","type":"story","content":"<p>Pandion opened the meeting with a stern expression, adjusting his glasses before speaking, \"Welcome everyone. As you have all been briefed, a Northi intelligence operative stationed in Telania has been reported missing for an extended period. We have reason to believe she has been murdered. If this is the case then her cover may have been compromised. More importantly, given her assignment, we\u0027re looking into the possibility that this is connected to the intelligence she was gathering on the Starfire Basilica.\"</p><p>He took a breath, \"To be more specific, the operative was assigned to monitor any unauthorized activities related to the Basilica, a weapon of mass destruction from the Great Divine War. The fact that her silence coincides with increased activity near the Basilica\u0027s known operational areas is concerning. We want to send a team to investigate. Due to the sensitive nature of this operation, the team needs to be small, discreet, and composed of members from different nations to maintain diplomatic balance. Any volunteers?\"</p><p>Shannon spoke up with her fan raised, \"Northi will be providing one of our own. Kori Itia from the Amethyst Company.\" Shannon waved her hand towards Kori, \"As the Amethyst Company doesn\u0027t officially exist on our records, this should provide the plausible deniability we need. Please treat her as an adventurer.\"</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-kori.png\" alt=\"Kori Itia, the Amethyst Company Operative\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Kori Itia, the Amethyst Company Operative</p></div>","chapter":1},{"title":"Assembling the Team","type":"story","content":"<p>The Easterner Delegation leader Aeriele stood up, \"Easter will send one of our own as well. Hjerngan of Sylvan, a High Fae swordsman. He has a lot of experience in diplomatic events, and was a participant in the Mirane Expedition.\" Aeriele announced, \"So he is no stranger to the dangers of the wider world. His honor and skill will serve this mission well.\"</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-aeriele.png\" alt=\"Aeriele of Easter\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Aeriele of Easter</p></div><p>The Bishop rubbed her chin, \"Why must it be a Chimera? Despite her skills, sending a non-human operative into Westria seems like a deliberate provocation. And do we truly trust Easter\u0027s contribution? Their \u0027Mirane Expedition\u0027 was as much about expanding their influence as it was about exploration.\"</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-bishop.png\" alt=\"The Westrian Bishop\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">The Westrian Bishop</p></div><p>Shannon raised a brow, \"And yet the Starfire Basilica threatens all of us equally, Bishop. Or do you suggest that Westria alone should manage the remnants of a weapon your own country created?\"</p><p>The Kiraran delegate narrowed their eyes, \"Kirara\u0027s stance remains neutral in this matter. However, we caution all parties against letting national pride hinder the investigation. The Basilica\u0027s technology transcends borders. We expect regular reports and transparency.\"</p><p>Pandion nodded, \"Agreed. Any other volunteers?\"</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Batta\u0027s Assignment","type":"story","content":"<p>The Bishop of the Church looked across the table, \"Westria shall be sending a paladin of the Grand Church for this endeavor. Batta will serve as the team leader, given that this operation takes place in Westrian territory.\"</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-batta.png\" alt=\"Batta, the Grand Paladin\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Batta, the Grand Paladin</p></div><p>Shannon frowned behind her fan, \"Maybe someone... other than Batta? It could be... bad for morale for any team she is on. Regardless of who it is.\"</p><p>The Bishop dismissed Shannon\u0027s concerns, \"Batta is one of our finest and most experienced paladins. Her presence ensures we maintain authority over the investigation\u0027s direction. This is non-negotiable.\"</p><p>Aeriele narrowed her gaze, \"Interesting choice. A Paladin known for excessive force leading a covert investigation. I assume Westria is not worried about maintaining the Basilica rather than dismantling it?\"</p><p>The Bishop\u0027s eye twitched, \"Watch your tongue, Faerie. We are fully committed to the disarmament agreement. Batta will ensure compliance.\"</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"A Sign of Good Faith","type":"story","content":"<p>Pandion sighed, \"Very well. Let\u0027s not forget the stakes here. We need results, not squabbles. Also, at the request of Westria\u0027s Church, we will be assigning Kane, a Westrian born member of the Mirane Expedition, to the team as a sign of good faith and cooperation between our nations.\"</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-kane.png\" alt=\"Kane, the Acolyte Knight\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Kane, the Acolyte Knight</p></div><p>The Bishop paused, \"Wait, Kane? Is he...? Hmm, very well. His ties to the Church could prove useful, even if his... associations are unconventional.\"</p><p>\"Additionally, Northi will be providing a communications specialist to the team. Fanea, a sheepfolk mage, will handle long-range communications and situational awareness. Also... she\u0027s a cutie so be nice to her.\"</p><p>Shannon cut off Pandion, \"Anyway. The team will consist of Batta, Kane, Kori, Hjerngan and Fanea. I believe this is a good group that has a wide range of skills.\"</p><p>Aeriele interjected, \"Let it be known that Easter expects full accountability. Any missteps in Westrian territory that harm our representative will be considered an act against the Accords.\"</p><p>The Bishop responded with a thin smile, \"Your concern for your representative is noted, Aeriele. Rest assured, Westria will ensure all participants are treated fairly... as long as they respect our sovereignty.\"</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Departure","type":"story","content":"<p>Pandion concluded, \"Then it\u0027s settled. The team departs within the week. Let\u0027s hope they find answers before the situation escalates.\"</p><p>As the delegates filed out, the undercurrents of mistrust and political maneuvering lingered in the air. Each nation harbored its own agenda, and the success of the mission depended not just on the team\u0027s abilities, but on navigating the treacherous waters of international politics. Pandion glanced out the window towards the gates of Mothergreen, his expression a mix of determination and apprehension.</p><p>The Bishop\u0027s eyes narrowed as she grit her teeth, \"Northi sending spies into our country is one thing, but the audacity of bringing non-humans to Westrian soil is another. Let us see how your \u0027balanced\u0027 team handles the realities of our homeland.\"</p><p>Shannon snapped her fan shut, \"And Westria\u0027s \u0027realities\u0027 better not include obstructing our investigation, Bishop. A reminder that the Basilica\u0027s disarmament was a condition of the peace treaty.\"</p><p>As the delegates departed, the team stood alone in the conference room. They had two days to prepare for their journey before their airship, The Crescent, would depart from Mothergreen to the Westrian coastal city of Telania.</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Aboard The Crescent","type":"story","content":"<p>The party gathers aboard The Crescent, a rather extravagant private airship. The vehicle had all the trimmings and was most likely paid for by the Westrian delegation. As the airship lifts off and is steadily in the air, the party finds themselves in the main salon, a spacious room filled with plush seating, a small bar, and wide windows offering a panoramic view of the clouds.</p><p>Kori sat cross-legged on one of the plush couches, her notebook splayed open in her lap with an ink pen in hand. The Amethyst Company operative had changed into more comfortable traveling clothes\u2014a fitted brown leather jacket over a green shirt, her guild\u0027s signature purple beret resting on the cushion beside her. Her long green braid hung over one shoulder, and her rabbit ears occasionally twitched at sounds from outside the salon.</p><p>She was reviewing the dossier she\u0027d been given, committing key details to memory. The missing operative, Niamh Campbell\u2014a canine chimera who had been embedded in Telania for two years under the guise of an artist. Last contact was approximately six weeks ago. The Starfire Basilica\u2014a weapon of mass destruction from the Divine War, supposedly dismantled per the peace treaty. And now, rumors of increased activity near its known sites.</p><p>She glanced up from her notes to survey her traveling companions. An odd group, to say the least.</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-kori2.png\" alt=\"Kori reviewing her notes aboard The Crescent\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Kori reviewing her notes aboard The Crescent</p></div>","chapter":1},{"title":"Getting Acquainted","type":"story","content":"<p>Hjerngan, tilting his head\u2014which was quite noticeable with antlers\u2014looked from person to person, to introduce himself and understand who he would need to cooperate with. \"I am Hjerngan of Sylvan, of House Sylvan. Swordsman by trade. I was sent here by the delegation of Easter, and I aim to represent its interests to the best of my abilities. I hope to get to know you all and establish trust between each and every one of us.\"</p><p>Kane nodded to each in turn. The big man\u0027s armor had been secured in the cargo hold, leaving him in a simple white shirt and dark trousers that did little to hide his imposing frame. \"It\u0027s a pleasure. I look forward to working with everyone.\" He pulled his large shield out and propped it nearby\u2014old habits died hard.</p><p>Kori looked up from her notebook and offered a small wave to the group. \"Kori Itia. I\u0027m an adventurer from Northi.\" She deliberately left out her guild affiliation, per Shannon\u0027s instructions. \"Pleased to be working with all of you.\"</p><p>Fanea gave a small bow from behind a particularly large cushion she\u0027d claimed as her own, her sheepfolk ears poking over the top. \"F-Fanea. Communications specialist. I\u0027ll be handling our long-range links and situational awareness.\" Her voice was soft, barely above a whisper.</p><p>Batta, who had been sprawled across the largest couch with her enormous club resting against the wall beside her, cracked one eye open. \"Batta. I\u0027m in charge. Don\u0027t die.\" She closed her eye again.</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Bonding Over Drinks","type":"story","content":"<p>Kori raised an eyebrow at the Grand Paladin\u0027s introduction but said nothing. She turned her attention to Kane and Hjerngan instead. They seemed the most approachable of the group. \"So, have either of you been to Westria before? I\u0027ve studied it extensively but never visited.\"</p><p>Kane studied the others carefully, his gaze more analytical than one might expect from a simple acolyte. \"I grew up in Westria originally. Orphanage in the northern reaches. I\u0027ve traveled broadly since then, but I haven\u0027t been back in some years. Things may have changed.\"</p><p>\"It\u0027s a common story... grew up an orphan in Northi, ward of the church.\" Kane continued with a thoughtful look, \"But the church gave me purpose and the skills I have now. I\u0027m grateful for that much.\"</p><p>\"I\u0027ve not been to Westria before, no. Barely left Easter most of my life until the Mirane Expedition.\" Hjerngan answered honestly, before continuing, \"I was recommended by Aeriele for this, and I feel some concern about how Chimera are treated in Westria. I hope it doesn\u0027t complicate things too much.\"</p><p>Kori nodded thoughtfully. She shared that concern deeply but didn\u0027t voice it. Instead she asked, \"What about you, Fanea? Have you been outside of Northi before?\"</p><p>Fanea shook her head, her ears bouncing. \"N-no, this is my first assignment abroad. Major Pandion said it would be a good learning experience.\" She fidgeted with the hem of her cloak.</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"A Tavern Incident","type":"story","content":"<p>On the second evening of the journey, the party found themselves in the airship\u0027s tavern\u2014a cozy establishment built into the lower deck. The warm amber light of artifice lanterns cast a pleasant glow over rough-hewn wooden tables.</p><p>Kori had ordered a local cider and was quietly enjoying it when a group of four Telanian guards who were also passengers began to get rowdy at a nearby table. Their voices grew louder with each drink, and it wasn\u0027t long before their attention turned to the non-human members of the party.</p><p>One of the armored guards\u2014clearly the drunkest of the bunch\u2014stood and swaggered over to where Kori was sitting. He leaned heavily on the table, his breath reeking of cheap ale. \"Well, well... what do we have here? A little knife-ear playing dress up as a person?\"</p><p>Kori\u0027s ears flattened beneath her beret. She\u0027d been dealing with this kind of thing her entire life. Her fingers tightened around her cider mug but she said nothing, keeping her expression carefully neutral.</p><p>The guard continued, emboldened by her silence and his companions\u0027 snickering. \"You know what I heard? I heard that rabbit folk are good for only one thing\u2014\"</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Kane\u0027s Defense","type":"story","content":"<p>Kane\u0027s chair scraped loudly against the floor as he stood, his full height casting a long shadow over the guard. The acolyte\u0027s necklace glinted in the lamplight as he spoke with calm authority.</p><p>\"It appears I\u0027ve already defended it quite well. She has been wonderful company during our trip and a kind, earnest traveling companion. I think you should broaden your horizons and learn to take each person you meet on their own merits. There are good and bad people everywhere. And identifying who is who has never been as simple as looking at their ears.\" Kane said with a sigh.</p><p>At the final statement from the armored fellow, he looked actually a bit incredulous. \"No hardship? She is literally being harassed by a random stranger during a meal right this very minute. Do you think this is a unique occurrence? If you were harassed anytime you went out to eat, would you not consider that a hardship? Take your seat and mull things over. I have a feeling I\u0027ve given you some things to think about... perhaps several people who have been listening and not intervening are going to think about it as well.\" Kane added while looking at the onlookers individually.</p><p>As the argument continued, the two at the bar seemed to think it was a great time to get out of there. They paid their tab and immediately left, not wanting to be embarrassed by their comrade.</p><p>The armored person pointed at Kane, \"So that\u0027s it... the only reason you\u0027re saying that is because this whore lays with you upon a whorebed. How can you dirty yourself with this animal? Everything you said is irrelevant because you\u0027re caught in her trap... you\u0027re being oppressed by her right now that you would forget about what her people did.\"</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"The Brawl","type":"story","content":"<p>The unknown person bellowed in a deep voice, \"I\u0027ll save you from yourself, brother.\"</p><p>They wound up the most obvious, most telegraphed right hand punch ever to be seen by the party\u2014likely for the rest of their lives.</p><p>Kane\u0027s eyes narrowed in response. \"You dare to suggest a man of the cloth has engaged in carnal behavior out of wedlock?\" Kane stated as holy light glowed from his eyes. If the drunken fool would even take notice, the acolyte\u0027s honors from his church had been around his neck the entire time.</p><p>Kori flickered and froze in place for a moment and an instant before, she appeared five feet away. The ghostly afterimage of her past self lingered in her vision and it would snap back to her shortly. But until then, she could reach back down that link in time to strike out, should she choose to.</p><p>The armored foe stumbled into Kori\u0027s chair in a confused state. Not understanding where Kori went, the armored person staggered forward and clocked Hjerngan in the face with an armored gauntlet.</p><p>Hjerngan was sitting down, thinking Kane had this situation handled, and wasn\u0027t paying much attention\u2014until he noticed too late a man stumbling into the chair where Kori used to be. What hurt more was not the force of the fist, but the loud \"clank\" of bone hitting the stone wall. His antler, as Hjerngan inspected the damage, was scuffed. Any sense of peace had turned to anger, and this poor man had no idea what he had wrought upon him.</p><p>Adeline rose from her seat and prepared to smash her water cup on the armored one, \"Oh goddess... are you alright, Kori?!\"</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Swift Justice","type":"story","content":"<p>Time stretched and bent as Kori threw a full powered punch directly at the armored guard\u0027s chest. In his drunken state, he barely reacted, and her fist tapped lightly against his armor. But to her eyes, a ghostly fist continued and froze in time just before impact. It would strike him the moment he let his guard down, if he\u0027d had a guard in the first place. She slid to the side, her past self streaking after her in her vision, and scrutinized the man. He wasn\u0027t really all there, drunken to near oblivion.</p><p>So she took her time and jabbed her knifed fingers up under the visor of his helmet and into the soft underside of his jaw. The blow rattled him so badly, he fell, tangling himself in the table and chairs.</p><p>The warrior at the bar immediately rose from his seat and walked over to the scene, stepping on the armored one and pinning him to the ground. He looked up at Kori, \"Yeah, sorry, that was really disgraceful. I was going to let him say whatever but once he attacked that was too much... especially after that pathetic argument.\" He gave a nod to Kane in appreciation for his good arguments. The warrior, clearly unaffiliated with the Telanian Guard, motioned to the other guards, \"Hey, get your friend out of here, they\u0027re piss drunk.\"</p><p>The other three seemed to want none of that spooky ghost magic that they saw Kori use and decided to pull out. Two of the guardsmen propped up their friend and began to drag them out of the bar. All four of them left.</p><p>After a few seconds, the door opened up one more time as one of the guardsmen walked back in. He looked at Kane with a pained expression that seemed one of shame for his comrades. It was at that moment that he mustered up the courage to shout, \"RABBIT FUCKER!\" The man ran away.</p>","chapter":1},{"title":"Aftermath and Arrival","type":"story","content":"<p>Hjerngan simply stood up from his chair. Breathing heavily, he looked down on the poor man stuck on the chair... and calmed down. \"We have a score to settle, however.\" He grabbed Kane\u0027s water, and calmly raised the glass over him. \"In my mercy, I will proclaim ourselves even for the indignity...\" and spilled the drink on his head slowly, while he was helpless.</p><p>\"Next time, I\u0027ll return like for like.\" Hjerngan stood taller than he had in a while. Then returned to his Misty Forest Select.</p><p>\"Don\u0027t worry about it, Kane. It\u0027s... it\u0027s a thing. I\u0027m used to it, most rabbitfolk are.\" Kori righted the chair the drunken man had knocked over and sat heavily. Miraculously, her cider hadn\u0027t been spilled in the brief scuffle.</p><p>\"And while we haven\u0027t known each other long, and I appreciate your vow of protection, please don\u0027t hesitate to rely on my skills as well.\"</p><p>Kane simply sighed as the group left, then blinked as he was called a certain name before the coward ran away. \"I think these fellows actually have a rabbitfolk fetish given their obsession with their private sex lives. They sure seem to like discussing it.\" He said while shaking his head before looking at Kori.</p><p>\"I am sorry my words were not enough to dissuade him at the start, Kori. I promised to protect all of you and I mean to keep it. I hope you can continue to rely on me... both of you...\" Kane said softly as he bowed politely in apology.</p><p>After the incident, the party ate their dinner as the sun set on their last day onboard The Crescent.</p><hr class=\"scene-break\"><p>As the party woke from their sleep, the airship had already been docked and was resupplying in the wait for clearance of disembarkation. Walking out onto the deck of the ship, the party would see the glimmering orange sun on the surface of the ocean.</p><p>Adeline led them down the gangway before stopping on the airship dock and turning around. With the sun behind her, creating a halo effect, she turned back towards the party. \"Welcome to Telania, my home.\"</p><div class=\"book-illustration\"><img src=\"books/img/ug-adeline.png\" alt=\"Adeline welcomes the party to Telania\"><p class=\"illustration-caption\">Adeline welcomes the party to Telania</p></div>","chapter":1},{"title":"Telania Morning","type":"story","content":"<h2>Episode 2 \u2014 A Precious Loss</h2><p>The dawn broke over the seaside town of Telania, a cold breeze creeping in through the window. Batta had decided it would be a great idea to open the door to the girls\u0027 room as she began to put on her armor.</p><p>It almost seemed like she did it to be a bit of an annoyance as she looked over at the sleeping Kori and Fanea with a strange smile.</p><p>The room was a wonderful seaside suite that had a slightly briny smell of seawater. It was furnished with quite high-quality wooden furniture, and the luxury of the room was apparent with a small wooden bowl of exotic fruits on the table.</p><p>The men\u0027s room was significantly smaller, almost as if Batta had purposely skimped on funds. It consisted of no dining area and simply two bunks that were reminiscent of their times onboard the airship. In fact, it seemed slightly more cramped.</p><p>Not particularly bothered by the small living quarters thanks to his youth, the only real bother was to change into his armor or into different clothing, which required Hjerngan to step out of the room. Standing at 7 foot 3 including the antlers, he had had a horrible sleep within the arranged rooms. He considered using his Fae step to simply sleep on the roof, but the midnight rainstorm stopped this plan.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Morning Preparations","type":"story","content":"<p>In his casual clothing procured just before the mission, Hjerngan would be birdwatching outside for species yet unseen to him, examining perhaps the only interesting wildlife in a city.</p><p>Waking up in a luxurious bed with the smell of the sea on the gentle breeze slipping through an open window was something Kori never thought she\u0027d experience. She\u0027d been able to stay in some pretty nice places in Northi on various missions but this suite was on a completely different level. When she had said her goodbyes to Adeline the evening before, she\u0027d been apprehensive when it became clear Batta had decided to split the group\u0027s lodgings between the men and women of their group. She almost didn\u0027t think she would have been able to sleep with the Westrian paladin in the same room but the bed had been so comfortable, she hadn\u0027t even noticed when she drifted off.</p><p>She hadn\u0027t meant to sleep in long enough for the sun to fully rise but she could skip one day of sword practice. Getting dressed in her guild uniform and armor under Batta\u0027s weird smile was disconcerting and she felt a little sheepish as she pulled on the purple Amethyst Company beret. It flattened and disguised her ears pretty effectively. Her thread daggers went into their disguised sheaths and her dueling sword attached to her hip.</p><p>Once Kori had her armor, weapons, and hat settled, she turned to Batta. \"So... what are the first steps we\u0027ll be taking? Do you have any contacts or leads?\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Batta\u0027s Orders","type":"story","content":"<p>Batta looked at Kori, staring at her ears in silence for a moment before responding, \"Well... I\u0027m going to check out the local temple and see if I can find any leads. I\u0027m a Grand Paladin so they will have to share information with me. You can take that girl with you and the boys...\"</p><p>She put a letter on the table, exchanging it for an apple from the basket, \"This letter proves that you\u0027re the friends and relatives of Niamh Campbell, the Northi spy. Go check out the body and see if you can find any clues. Since you\u0027re from Northi, you must know of some strange way they hide messages... perhaps in their ass?\" Batta gave a twisted and creepy smile before locking eyes with Kori and taking a bite from the apple.</p><p>She paused for a moment as she rolled her fingers, the apple falling from her hand and onto the floor, \"Sour. I hate these border towns.\" Batta left with a slam of the door.</p><p>The sound shook Fanea awake who wiped her eyes and looked over at Kori, \"Where is Batta going?\"</p><p>Kane was finishing off the simple breakfast of sausage and bread with a bit of tea he acquired, out of pocket because it seems that wasn\u0027t included in their lodgings either, just as he was stepping out the front of the inn, enjoying the slowly rising warmth of the sunlight as he stood out beside Hjerngan.</p><p>\"If you hadn\u0027t eaten yet you should... I get a feeling we\u0027re in for a long day... and dress to work I say. We already stand out enough as is.\" He said while taking a sip from the too-small cup. Quirking an eyebrow as Batta strode out of the inn with purpose and moved past them with nary a good morning.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Morgue","type":"story","content":"<p>The party shortly headed over towards the morgue. Walking through the market in the early morning they would see stalls opening up for breakfast that day.</p><p>As they were walking, Fanea actually spoke to Kori, \"Batta didn\u0027t let me cast my spell before she left, so I don\u0027t know how we will contact her.\"</p><p>Pausing, she whispered an incantation as a magical pulse shot out from her and around the party members, \"Link Sense. Now we can communicate even over long distances.\"</p><p>Communications Mages were a staple of special operations in which immediate and clear information was required. If it wasn\u0027t for the difficult training required, it would be no doubt that every military unit would have one. Sheepfolk in particular were known for their aptitude in this special skill.</p><p>Fanea seemed to be an incredibly shy person. She fidgeted a bit every time she spoke and seemed uncomfortable. The sheepfolk stopped at one of the stalls as they were walking, quickly snatching up four grilled eggs on a stick with a sweet glaze. She handed them to the others, \"Hmm... Westrian Breakfast food... since Batta ate all of the food...\"</p><p>Kori didn\u0027t even know that there was breakfast served to the room... but the random pile of empty plates near the fruit bowl that were licked clean started to make more sense.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"A Cold Welcome","type":"story","content":"<p>Kori led the party to the Telanian morgue which was a building slightly to the west of the city center. The morgue building was cold and dry, with artifice lanterns hanging from the ceiling in a soft, eerie glow. As doors to the back opened, a slight musty smell began to fill the room as the attendant appeared.</p><p>She was a middle-aged woman with pallid skin and long, stringy black hair that had most of it tied back into a tight bun. Her long black dress was stained with various fluids and substances, and was adorned with a few religious symbols made in intricate embroidery.</p><p>She looked at them with her dull, sunken eyes that were a deep shade of grey and spoke in the voice of one who hadn\u0027t slept in some time. \"Huh? Hmm... what do you want?\"</p><p>Kori waited for a moment before remembering she had the letter. She pulled it out of her pocket and unfolded it before handing it over to the woman.</p><p>\"We\u0027re here for Niamh Campbell.\" She let her Northi accent thicken just a little bit.</p><p>The morgue worker\u0027s eyes twitched, \"Again...? At least it\u0027s finally the family. She has no family in this town. Her best friend is here \u0027visiting.\u0027 Who visits a morgue multiple times? Creepy and weird.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Marianne","type":"story","content":"<p>The party entered the morgue, which was divided into several sections. Each section was designated for different stages of preparation. Most of the work was done in the other rooms, and the party members could hear the soft murmurs of attendants and the gentle rustlings of cloth. In the final room they would see the body of a canine chimera woman, a woman in a green dress sobbing over her body.</p><p>The woman placed a painting beside the body, a painting of the deceased, \"I made this for you... I hope you can look at it in the afterlife.\" She continued to sob.</p><p>Kane gently walked up alongside the crying woman. \"That\u0027s a very beautiful gesture to make. I am certain their eyes will fall upon it as well as you in the next.\" He said softly as he grabbed hold of his necklace and said a soft mumbling prayer to himself while waving a hand over the deceased.</p><p>\"Were you very close?\" He asked lightly.</p><p>The woman wiped her eyes and glanced up at Kane, \"She was... my best friend...\" She wrapped her fingers around the cloth of her dress and squeezed.</p><p>Marianne looked to Kane with tearful eyes that glistened in a prismatic shine despite the dim light, \"Brother, thank you... I just... she was such a close friend to me for these past two years. The truth is... I\u0027m the one who found her... and her body didn\u0027t even have the time to grow cold.\"</p><p>She sniffled, \"I wish for justice... but I know that people in Telania can be a bit... you know. Since she\u0027s a Chimera... But even as a Chimera she was the most wonderful friend and I can\u0027t bear to imagine how lonely she was... in those last moments. Brother, can you bring this up with the church? Find out what happened to her? I know the Church doesn\u0027t deem it worth the time but could you for a lost soul like me?\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Investigating the Body","type":"story","content":"<p>\"We\u0027re here to find out exactly that, miss,\" Kori assured gently. \"We\u0027d like to examine Niamh more closely, if you\u0027ll allow it?\"</p><p>\"I am but a friend, you are family... you should do what you must,\" Marianne nodded, \"Especially if it would help to find out who would do this!\"</p><p>Kori fought back a frown and gestured toward the rest of the group. There wasn\u0027t much more she could do to blunt searching the body and she didn\u0027t think she\u0027d discover anything new. Not checking wasn\u0027t an option. Most likely, Niamh\u0027s body had already been thoroughly searched and any effects would be with her effects stored with the morgue staff.</p><p>The first obvious thing was her throat had been slit. It wasn\u0027t subtle but it was clean. Likely, she hadn\u0027t even been able to struggle before it was done.</p><p>Kane held his necklace as he spoke a prayer softly to himself while inspecting her neck wound, thinking to himself: <em>Was a single stroke of a short blade... no sign of struggle or resistance. Either she \"trusted\" her assailant, or it happened so fast she didn\u0027t realize she was dead. Both of those are troubling answers...</em></p><p>Kneeling down to Marianne\u0027s level, Hjerngan tried to be candid. \"Well, Miss Marianne, you\u0027ve painted a beautiful portrait. I see a lot of passion in each stroke. Much like my sister\u0027s woodcarvings.\" He gave a smile. \"It\u0027s clear to anyone that a lot of love went into it.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Mortician\u0027s Insults","type":"story","content":"<p>Kane approached the Mortician and nodded respectfully. \"I\u0027ll be needing the personal effects to provide to the family. We also need to start the process for releasing the remains as well.\"</p><p>The Mortician seemed a bit relieved for some reason that Kane was the one to approach her at the desk and not one of the \u0027others.\u0027 \"Alright... I\u0027ll bring the things. They\u0027re going to the family though, right? But brother... don\u0027t you think it\u0027s a little strange? I mean she\u0027s a rabbitfolk... the deceased is a catfolk. Do they really have big animal orgies outside of Westria?\"</p><p>Her face was clearly filled with disgust.</p><p>She moved to the back room and pulled out a box and placed it onto the table, \"Well normally this would be at the guard station but... they said it was obviously a suicide. As a mortician I\u0027d have to disagree... but I mean yeah, whatever. Many such cases.\"</p><p>As the party headed to the main lobby of the morgue, the Mortician gave Kori the once over and asked bluntly, \"Out of curiosity, what is your going rate? Asking for a friend. Never seen a rabbitfolk before but I can see the appeal.\"</p><p>Insults to himself Hjerngan could deal with, but that crossed a line. With a reflexive look of disgust, he spoke without thinking, \"And for an ugly hag, that will stay a curiosity,\" before storming out the door.</p><p>Kori froze mid-step and looked over her shoulder at the mortician. \"Twenty thousand,\" she said nonchalantly. \"And thirty thousand more per person in groups. And I never agree to more than five at a time.\" The mortician didn\u0027t need to know that the amount she gave was Amethyst Company\u0027s going rate for assassinations.</p><p>\"Frankly, you can\u0027t afford me.\" Without a backwards glance, she stepped out of the mortuary.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Niamh\u0027s House","type":"story","content":"<p>The midday sun was beginning to reach its highest point in the sky as the party headed down the small cobblestone path that led to Niamh\u0027s house.</p><p>The house had a cute, simple design with cut stone married with wood. A simple oak door was adorned with a bit of iron reinforcement and was partnered with a small window. Capping the house was a roof made out of clay shingles and a clay smokestack for a simple fireplace.</p><p>Much to Hjerngan\u0027s delight, she had a small herb and flower garden.</p><p>Marianne walked them up the cobblestone path towards the house, \"I was here that evening. I saw the lights on inside the house. Only the upstairs light was on. I couldn\u0027t really tell anything was wrong until I got to the house itself and I didn\u0027t see anyone.\"</p><p>Kori carefully examined the house, taking in the details before slowly turning to give the same scrutiny to the other houses she could see in the near distance. They\u0027d had to travel to the outskirts of Telania and the houses this far out had rather large plots to themselves. It gave each plot a good deal of privacy and had plenty of room for personal gardens or lines of trees on the property perimeter. Unless someone had been specifically watching, it was very unlikely that any of the neighbors saw anything suspicious.</p><p>It was a pretty decent place to house a spy.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Crime Scene","type":"story","content":"<p>As Kori finished climbing the stairs, it was immediately obvious Niamh had been murdered upstairs in her loft. A large bloodstain painted the floor between the stairs and the one window. A desk was placed beneath that window, likely to allow work to be done by daylight. Tucked against one wall was a single person bed and placed on every other available wall surface were dressers and cabinets.</p><p>She slowly paced around the stain, careful not to touch any part of it, and held a hand up to her ear to begin narrating out to the rest of the group her findings. It was clean, for a bloodstain. Very little splatter, no splashes on the walls or the desk. No footprints disturbing it nor was there any sign that a body blocked any of the blood spray from the front. So Niamh had likely been attacked from behind while facing the stairs.</p><p>The temptation to immediately search the desk was strong but she still wanted to know how the killer had gained entry. There was dirt on the windowsill and the desk, clear oily fingerprints on the window pane, and smudged ink on one of the papers a booted foot had dragged over. It was the singularly most amateur break-in she had ever seen. Children back home were more professional.</p><p>The desk held unused paper and pens with a single letter that was half written. It was addressed to someone in Northi but it had also been the paper stepped on. However, stuck to the underside of the desk was a hastily written note with nonsense on it.</p><p><em>\"Perfect,\"</em> she thought, <em>\"a cipher.\"</em></p><p>She carefully folded the note and tucked it into a pocket. She would find out what \"Ehzduh wkh Lqkrqv lq wkh Gfnnv, 2X-30\" meant later.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Cracking the Cipher","type":"story","content":"<p>After the party had set up the barrier and had instructed Marianne to re-set up her alarm, they headed back towards their tavern. They had exchanged information with Marianne in case they needed to meet up later.</p><p>The sun had begun its descent with the skies aflame in an orange and violet hue. They had finally arrived back where they had started that morning. The door opened to the girls\u0027 room and Batta was already sitting there at the table, eating a large piece of meat on a bone. She didn\u0027t even bother to finish chewing as she spoke, \"Where the hell were you guys the whole day?\"</p><p>Hjerngan was the first to get in a remark, with a sharp and hostile expression. \"Doing our jobs.\"</p><p>Kori cut a quick glance to Kane and Hjerngan before she began to explain about their investigation at the morgue, meeting Marianne, and following the subsequent lead to Niamh\u0027s home near the edge of the city.</p><p>\"...and as far as we could determine, the three attackers had no time to seriously search the house and missed this.\" She pulled the carefully folded coded message from a pocket and held it out to Batta. \"We haven\u0027t had any time to go over it yet but it\u0027s not a cipher any of us immediately recognized.\"</p><p>Batta looked over the cipher and nodded to herself in comprehension, \"Ah I see... hmm...\" She spent an entire minute only nodding and muttering to herself before handing the note back to Kori. She replied, \"Yeah.\" She shrugged. \"Don\u0027t really care to figure it out. You guys can just do your jobs.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Beware the Lions","type":"story","content":"<p>As Hjerngan was looking over the cipher, Kori looked over his shoulder. Under his antlers, he looked at the cipher that both Kane and himself worked for the better part of half an hour. \"We\u0027re so close I feel it, but we\u0027re missing a few essential clues...\"</p><p>Meanwhile, Batta scratched her head, \"Yeah. It seems that there\u0027s a group called the Euphoric Front. I heard they collect the ears of rabbitfolk. They\u0027re a human separatist movement that doesn\u0027t trust all of you others.\" Her eyes darted to Kori, Hjerngan and then to Fanea.</p><p>When Kane began to work on the cipher, Hjerngan chose a more productive method to get out of talking with Batta and elected to help him with exactly that. Kane managed to work out several parts of it: \"beware the oirnv in the grfnv\"</p><p>Kori dredged up the memories of cryptography courses she\u0027d taken at the guild. At least one letter stood out as both common and as part of small words. It was just a quick bit of mental math and some embarrassingly simple finger counting. Just as the two were triumphantly writing down the word \"Beware,\" she finished solving it.</p><p>\"Beware the Lions of the Docks,\" she read. \"You guys did a pretty good job, but there\u0027s an easier way to do this. I\u0027ll have to show you sometime.\"</p><p>Hjerngan snapped a pencil in half when his hard work was single-handedly upstaged. In a calm voice, he simply let out his frustration with two words. \"Yes... let\u0027s...\"</p><p>Batta nodded, \"Ah I see. We should go investigate once the sun comes down. Less commotion in case we need to interrogate anyone.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Warehouse Raid","type":"story","content":"<p>The party waited until nightfall and then headed to the docks. Whiffs of seawater were in the air, along with the occasional mist from a tall wave. Looking down at the docks from a cliffside, the party surveyed the area.</p><p>Fanea\u0027s voice was heard in their minds, \"I found a slightly suspicious place. The warehouses near the lighthouse are being patrolled by heavily armed individuals. Probably where to start.\"</p><p>Batta raised to her feet, her heavy cloak fluttering, \"Alright, seems good. If they have anything to hide they\u0027ll tell me. I\u0027ll go ask, and if that doesn\u0027t go well then we know this is the place. Wait and observe. If it goes poorly then head in immediately so they don\u0027t have time to transport or hide anything. I\u0027ll handle whatever comes in the distraction.\"</p><p>\"Somehow I doubt they\u0027ll tell you willingly... only through blood-curdled screams of horror, maybe.\" As much as Hjerngan wanted to test his mettle against opponents, he knew that this was not the way to conduct an investigation. \"Is there any other more subtle approach? Especially when we\u0027ve been warned explicitly by a dead woman of these murderers.\"</p><p>\"Huh? Subtle? Don\u0027t be a Faerie.\"</p><p>Batta headed down around the right side of the building. It wasn\u0027t long before one of the workers there who was armed with a sword came to stop her. The party could hear only Batta\u0027s words through the communication magic.</p><p>\"Just wondering what\u0027s going on here. It\u0027s an inspection. Huh? From who? From me. I\u0027m inspecting because I want to.\"</p><p>The worker unsheathed her sword and in one quick motion, Batta pulled the giant club from her back and smashed it into the ground. A pink mist filled the air as a splatter appeared along the wall.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Into the Fray","type":"story","content":"<p>\"Let\u0027s move, quickly. While they\u0027re distracted,\" Kori urged. She raised a hand to her ear to transmit via the communication spell. \"Fanea, guide us in, please?\"</p><p>Fanea\u0027s voice could be heard in their minds, \"There are a few people inside there... um... three with a high spirit core signature, but there are seven total. It seems pretty dangerous. If you keep going straight and hang a right there are a set of double doors. They\u0027re in the warehouse, but there\u0027s a bit of chaos over what might be happening. Most of the guards are gone now and are heading to Batta.\"</p><p>Kori led the group to the double doors. She took a quick glance into the warehouse, noted the stacks of boxes that would be perfect to hide behind.</p><p>\"I\u0027ll get inside to the right. If they spot me, come in at once, but if not, I\u0027ll give a signal and I can hit them from the flank as you come in.\"</p><p>Kori slipped into the warehouse, timing her movements to the commotion Batta was making in the distance. She took up a position behind a pile of crates with no alarm being raised.</p><p>She watched Kane sneak in, with only the combat outside letting his clanking steps get inside without alerting anyone. And then he rounded the boxes in full view of exactly the woman Fanea warned them about.</p><p>The woman in the kimono pointed at Kane, \"Intruder! What are you doing here? This is private property.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"First Spring Rain","type":"story","content":"<p>\"I heard a commotion when I was out enjoying the ocean air and came to investigate.\" His acolyte trappings clearly visible. \"I heard a sound of someone in pain and thought someone needed help.\" He said as he took steps toward her in feigned concern.</p><p>The kimono woman narrowed her eyes, \"The screaming outside? And you come here in full armor with a weapon? Ellia, search this man...\"</p><p>Kane sighed as she reached for his shield and immediately followed around it with a swat to her head. \"I\u0027m afraid I can\u0027t let you do that. Oh well... the direct approach is fine.\" He said with a small smile.</p><p>The kimono woman widened her stance and unsheathed a katana from within her bamboo parasol. She did a full spin and threw the parasol into the air. She took in a deep breath gripping the katana with both hands, \"Victory for the swift. Esoteric Art: First Spring Rain.\"</p><p>A barrage of senbon needles appeared from seemingly nowhere, raining upon Kane. While a few deflected from his armor, many struck in between the joints and a few dug into his shoulders. Blood began to trickle down from him.</p><p>Time twisted and snapped together as Kori linked herself more closely to her past self. She dashed forward, pulling at her future potential and swung out with her thread daggers. Her present self swung at empty air and her past self\u0027s dagger sank into the unsuspecting back of the kimono-clad woman.</p><p>Nacina yelled at Kori, \"A whore! A rabbit-eared whore! If you damaged my umbrella I\u0027m going to kill you like I did that cat!\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Nacina\u0027s Defeat","type":"story","content":"<p>Kori stared down Nacina as she counted down in her head. \"I\u0027ll accept your surrender but you\u0027ll need to stay long enough for our superior to question you.\"</p><p>\"If you don\u0027t, you\u0027ll go the same way as him,\" she gestured toward Alan\u0027s retreating form and snapped her fingers. The man stumbled and collapsed suddenly.</p><p>Nacina swallowed hard and her eyes went wide, \"Who are you people...\"</p><p>Kori twirled her daggers absently in her hands. \"The Amethyst Company. And I\u0027m not hearing you say \u0027I surrender,\u0027 Miss Nacina.\"</p><p>Kane took off like a bolt after the fleeing heavy knight. Striking into her heavily as he caught up. \"My allies are most capable. I\u0027m afraid you will not be rid of me that easily unless you kill me,\" he stated with a grin.</p><p>Ellia noticed just in time to spin her greatsword around to meet Kane\u0027s attack, \"You win this one... but our Priestess and our Champion will avenge us. I\u0027m nothing compared to Addy. So go on, do your worst, my misled brother. You\u0027re fighting for the wrong side.\"</p><p>\"What that thing did and how it goes against everything right. Any side that sacrifices the innocent or their own people for such a vile weapon is very clearly the wrong side.\" He said, shaking his head in disapproval.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Aftermath","type":"story","content":"<p>In the aftermath, Nacina had escaped, but many of the Euphoric Front members were killed. Hjerngan managed to gather 3 prisoners. Outside, the party had taken the remaining prisoners to take them to Batta, who was surrounded by roughly twenty corpses that were pulverized into minced meat.</p><p>\"Oh. You guys lived, huh? Neat.\" She smashed her club into one of the girls that was begging for her life.</p><p>Fanea\u0027s mote of light spun and then shot out of the warehouse and went after Nacina. The operator\u0027s voice could be heard by all, \"I\u0027ll meet you back at the base. I have to cancel the group communication spell if I\u0027m going to track her over long range. Is that okay?\"</p><p>Kori considered for a moment and nodded before remembering she needed to trigger the spell. \"That should be fine. We\u0027ll need to stick around to secure the warehouse anyway. We don\u0027t have the ability to chase her down right now.\"</p><p>Batta held her hand to her ear while she ground her club into the fallen, \"Yeah. We should track. It\u0027s more important. We need to be quick here. If she leads us to their base, we need to attack before they have time to recoup their forces.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Assault Begins","type":"story","content":"<p>The party began heading to the site where the runner escaped to. As they neared the area of operation, Fanea re-established the telepathic link between them.</p><p>Batta calmly spoke as they walked through the brush, \"When we get there... I\u0027ll move on ahead through the first group. If they are trying to rebuild the superweapon, then they\u0027ll be immediately evacuating it to a safer location since they won\u0027t want to risk it. I\u0027ll go ahead and recover it. You just make sure I don\u0027t get stabbed in the back. Also, you guys should die if you have to because this mission is that important.\" She said so nonchalantly.</p><p>\"All we can do is follow in your wake, Batta, and secure a choke point. We\u0027ll hold them. We have to.\" The idea of any superweapon falling into the hands of these maniacs was something that couldn\u0027t even be considered. All of their lives were worth the cost in preventing it.</p><p>\"And Fanea, don\u0027t hesitate to call for help. We still have to take that tour after, right?\"</p><p>Fanea was flustered by the comment, \"Yeah... I can\u0027t wait.\"</p><p>Batta looked at Fanea and then to Kori with a twisted grin, \"Heh. Gay.\" Batta moved away from the group and began to look over her weaponry.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Quarry","type":"story","content":"<p>Their target was an open quarry with starfire ore deposits visible sporadically along the walls. Twelve humans with guns patrolled the interior of the quarry nervously and Nacina was pacing along the highest point in the center overseeing some sort of evacuation. Judging by the heavy boxes being moved out of the north side of the quarry, she was sure either their target or something critical to its repair was already being moved. A dam was set in the northeast portion of the quarry.</p><p>She quickly began relaying her observations to the rest of the group and urged Batta to begin moving immediately to swing wide around the quarry to intercept the evacuation from the north.</p><p>\"I\u0027ll circle east to get to the dam over there,\" she pointed. \"If I get spotted, I\u0027ll take cover and start working on the musketeers in the lower level. You two need to rush the central platform as quickly as you can.\"</p><p>Hjerngan knelt down in a sprinting position, just before the woodlands ended. He got ready, like a tiger who spots his prey, and leapt out from the trees like a majestic deer, with all eyes on him as time almost slowed down for the onlookers. The traditional sylvan claymore reflecting the dawn\u0027s light, before he disappeared in thin air for just a moment in glittering green and gold, appearing in the middle of the quarry, his blade already landed into a bloody mess of a woman, before lifting it up again, ready for the chaos to come.</p><p>Batta laughed maniacally in the distance, which drew the attention of the Euphoric Front guards.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Adeline\u0027s Betrayal","type":"story","content":"<p>A perceivable rustling noise was heard behind Kori as a humanoid stepped out from the brush, dusting themselves off.</p><p>\"Ah... shoot...\"</p><p>She paused as she saw the girl before her.</p><p>\"K...Kori? What are you doing here?\"</p><p>Kori had to quickly pull on the connecting thread of her dagger to yank it back into her hand before it could get anywhere near Adeline. Her attention quickly snapped back to the fight unfolding in the quarry.</p><p>She didn\u0027t have time to have a lengthy discussion with Adeline as she gauged the path and distance to the sniper. \"Stopping the bad guys,\" she said quickly.</p><p>Adeline looked down at the ground, her mouth wrinkling into a frown, \"Kori... get out of here please... I\u0027m serious. It\u0027s really dangerous... you shouldn\u0027t be sightseeing here...\" The girl slowly slipped her hand behind her lower back.</p><p>Kori felt a chill run down her spine and the unbidden thought that Adeline was with the Euphoric Front slashed through her mind.</p><p>\"Hold that thought,\" she said as she dug out a potion she had just obtained. It had the slogan \"As fast as a bunny girl!\" and the character of a rabbitfolk woman discarding clothing as its logo. Reluctantly, she downed the potion.</p><p>\"Be right back!\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Champion Revealed","type":"story","content":"<p>Adeline frowned as Kori ran away. Calmly, she walked to the edge of the platform, slowly unsheathing a dagger from a sheath behind her. She threw the dagger a ridiculous distance at Hjerngan.</p><p>As the dagger missed and landed on the ground beside Hjerngan, she shouted out, \"Mallow!\" The girl disappeared in a flash of light, appearing in a burst of light underneath Hjerngan as she grabbed the dagger and stabbed it into him.</p><p>Nacina winced from her wounds as she turned to Adeline, \"It\u0027s about time, Addy! Where the hell were you?!\"</p><p>Adeline turned to Kane as she positioned her rapier in a defensive position, \"You\u0027re a human too... can\u0027t you just leave? If you leave we won\u0027t pursue you...\"</p><p>\"If I leave, every death and innocent soul sacrificed for your vile ambition on each side will be my fault. You act like I\u0027m fighting to save just non-humans. I\u0027m fighting to save all of you... you just don\u0027t understand... none of you seem to...\" Kane said sadly. \"Why do you wish to spread so much death? It\u0027s so much more rewarding to spread life. No... I\u0027ll not leave. It\u0027s not because I\u0027m human... it\u0027s because I am merely alive.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Kori vs. Adeline","type":"story","content":"<p>Kori\u0027s form blurred as the future and past bent. She stepped to the side, a ghostly image remaining in her place as she lashed out at both Adeline and the musketeer, her past self echoing her blows. Time twisted to delay the blows she landed and she took the opening the ghostly attacks made to land powerful sneak attacks on her targets. The musketeer fell and Adeline staggered from the blows.</p><p>The duel with Adeline around and across the rocky platform was a flurry of blows, positioning and narrow dodges. Adeline seemed to be on her last legs and was using her Divine Arm to keep Kori at arm\u0027s length. But Kori knew she was faster and all it would take was a single misstep to end it.</p><p>\"Please, just stop this, Adeline!\"</p><p>Adeline exchanged more blows with Kori as she shouted, \"I can\u0027t... I have to protect my family!\"</p><p>She didn\u0027t stop and Kori stopped holding back. All it took was a single flashbang and three quick strikes for her to end it. Normally, she would have ripped her dagger out of her opponent with the connected wire and moved onto the next target but... Adeline didn\u0027t deserve that. Kori approached the downed woman and slid her rapier out of reach before kneeling next to her.</p><p>\"I\u0027m sorry it had to end this way,\" she said, exhaustion clear in her voice.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Adeline\u0027s Last Words","type":"story","content":"<p>Adeline looked up at Kori, \"I... I wish we could\u0027ve been friends instead... Kori. Please be nice to Mallow... she gets jealous so please... don\u0027t use any special weapons near her, ok...\" She pointed to First Spring Rain. She began to sob as she coughed blood, \"This world is so cruel... I\u0027m sorry... Jessica... Mariel... Jacob... Arl...\"</p><p>Her body grew still as she dropped her dagger beside her.</p><p>Hjerngan was hurt badly. Three times did the rogue\u0027s daggers try for his heart. All he could do was look towards the sky and hope the others won. Though the sounds of combat ending frightened his heart, all he could hear was the telepathy confirming they won, but he couldn\u0027t bring himself to smile.</p><p>Fanea responded, \"That was really close... I\u0027ll head over right now with my medkit. Just give me a...\" There was a loud screech as the telepathy spell suddenly ended.</p><p>\"Gah... damn... Fanea! We need to get back to her right away,\" Kane exclaimed.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Batta\u0027s True Colors","type":"story","content":"<p>With tears stinging at her eyes, Kori reluctantly slid First Spring Rain off her back and set it next to Nacina\u0027s body before she gingerly picked up the Divine Arm, Mallow.</p><p>Kori took Adeline\u0027s hand as she breathed her last. \"I will do everything I can to make this world a safer place for Jessica and Mariel and Jacob and Arlon and Christina and Shina. And everyone! So don\u0027t worry, Adeline; I\u0027ll take care of everything in your place.\"</p><p>The party arrived at their base to see a figure wearing the robes of a Church of Light Priestess. She stood over Fanea who was bleeding from her nose, leaning against a tree but still breathing.</p><p>The Priestess looked at them, \"Oh? You\u0027re still alive? That\u0027s...\" She noticed Mallow in Kori\u0027s hand, \"Hmm... how did you... tch... she was too soft as I thought.\"</p><p>Emerging from the bushes was Batta, her bloody club on her shoulder. The Paladin stood before the Priestess, grinning. \"So this is it, huh?\"</p><p>Hjerngan wasted no time, Fae-Stepping in between the Priestess and Fanea, and attacked with a flurry of blows.</p><p>Batta intercepted the strikes with her massive club and softly knocked Hjerngan away, \"So hasty... I\u0027d like you if you weren\u0027t a disgusting tree hugger.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"A Precious Loss","type":"story","content":"<p>Kane\u0027s eyes narrowed as Batta stood before them after knocking Hjerngan aside. \"So what is all this, Batta? Just casually killing members for your own amusement? To pass time up until this moment?\"</p><p>Batta looked at Kane and narrowed her eyes before laughing out loud, \"What? Killing members? I didn\u0027t do this...\"</p><p>She pointed her club at Fanea.</p><p>\"But you know what... I\u0027ll oblige you.\"</p><p>She wound her arm back and smashed her massive club into Fanea, caving in her ribs while taking care to not hit Kori.</p><p>\"There... now you\u0027re telling the truth, Kane. Such an upstanding man, I couldn\u0027t stand to see you become a liar.\"</p><p>The Priestess raised a hand to her mouth and coughed, \"Unnecessary.\"</p><p>Batta shrugged, \"Alright, get out of here you guys. Go home.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"A Bitter Retreat","type":"story","content":"<p>Hjerngan was dumbstruck in a moment of pure disbelief, before he pulled himself together and rushed to Fanea\u0027s side, lending her his shoulder to carry her out of there.</p><p>Batta grinned at Kane, \"Yeah me too but... you see... I haven\u0027t been seeing as much action since the war ended. I kinda miss those days. Priestess here says I can join them, the Euphoric Front. Sounds fun, I think.\"</p><p>The Priestess pointed at the three, \"Well your first assignment is to kill them... and retrieve Mallow, the Divine Arms. I need to find a more suitable wielder.\"</p><p>Batta clicked her tongue, \"That\u0027s not fair. They won fair and square. I respect the strong. I actually don\u0027t dislike them... that much. Well, you guys get out of here before the Priestess throws a fit.\"</p><p>Kori flinched as the club whistled by her and slammed into Fanea, the crunch of the blow seemed to rattle her own chest. Whatever Batta was saying, Kane was saying, was just white noise. Hjerngan was already trying to get Fanea up but Kori could already tell it was fruitless. The sheer damage\u2014on top of whatever injuries she\u0027d suffered before they\u0027d arrived? The potions in her pocket were useless.</p><p>She knelt next to Hjerngan and placed a gentle hand on his shoulder. \"She\u0027s gone... but we can at least not leave her here.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Oaths in the Dark","type":"story","content":"<p>\"So be it... I will do all in my power to bring whatever comes to a swift end. I took an oath to protect the weak and mend the ill. And unfortunately it seems there is only one cure for an illness like yours. You will find joy in it, I suppose. But that is not my concern in the end. I\u0027m not here to be your final judge... only to arrange your meeting with them as soon as possible.\" Kane said with a calm demeanor.</p><p>Kane then turned and helped Kori and Hjerngan with Fanea to make their exit.</p><p>Batta smiled, \"Have a good journey. I\u0027ll see you soon.\"</p><p>The Priestess seemed disgusted in Batta, unable to do anything but watch their precious weapon disappear into the woods.</p><hr class=\"scene-break\"><p>Not returning to Telania, the party made a slow trek to the nearby village of Pinetree where they were able to meet with a Northi contact. After nearly two weeks of hiding out, an airship appeared at Pinetree\u0027s one airship dock.</p><p>Purchasing materials to prevent the body from rotting, the party boarded the airship and headed back to Mothergreen.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Return to Mothergreen","type":"story","content":"<p>Onboard the airship, Kane would be greeted by the ship\u0027s pilot.</p><p>Nix gave Kane the once over, \"You look like shit... what happened?\"</p><p>Shelly, another member of Angel\u0027s Sword, came to help them with the body. She knew better than to say anything.</p><p>The weeks did nothing to temper Hjerngan\u0027s wrath. \"We were betrayed by that Westrian battle-drunk maniac,\" he blurted bluntly.</p><p>Kori quietly handed the airship pilot her journal, the record of their journey had been difficult to complete at the end, but it needed to be. For Adeline and Fanea, at least.</p><p>Kane looked at Nix with a soft smile. \"Not to worry, Miss Nix... was just a lot of passionate arguments from people... they just decided to use a bit more than words. An unfortunate part of this big body is I\u0027m very easy to have discussions with.\" He said with a hearty laugh and lightly patted Nix\u0027s shoulder.</p><p>Before the rituals of Kane\u0027s mornings, Hjerngan himself would have terrible nightmares within the airship. The nights spent hiding out were done a good distance away from the rest of his members, mingling very little. The events of Telania did not sit well with him, and disturbed him on a deeper level. Most of all, the betrayal of Fanea by Batta, while expected, was beyond acceptable. It disgusted him and all that was right in the world, and his dreams reflected this. He\u0027d not sleep well for a long time.</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"The Debriefing","type":"story","content":"<p>Several weeks later, at the debriefing for the mission, they would come to the same round table they had met at before. After giving their reports, rather than asking about Fanea\u0027s body, the Priestess wasted no time.</p><p>\"The Westrian Church demands the surrender of the Divine Arms, Mallow, to our custody. The weapon is of Westrian origin and it\u0027s only right for us to have it.\"</p><p>The Priestess didn\u0027t even bother to look at Kori.</p><p>Hjerngan himself would enter the meeting with the Faerie Light Eyes, after isolating himself from the group. He gave a truly horrid look to the Priestess.</p><p>Kori tapped her fingers on the table, very conscious of Mallow sheathed at the small of her back. She had carefully omitted Mallow\u0027s name and description from the report, on the advice of Major Lapis. She\u0027d only described an \"unknown Divine Arms\" in use by one of the leaders of the Euphoric Front.</p><p>\"I\u0027m not sure I know what you\u0027re talking about. There wasn\u0027t any mention of a, what was it? Mallow? in our report. If the Westrian Church has managed to lose a Divine Arms, perhaps you could contract out a guild mission to locate it.\"</p>","chapter":2},{"title":"Political Fallout","type":"story","content":"<p>\"Interesting to make demands after you both betray the entire mission put forward at this very table... and then have the audacity to make a request as if you were the ones who had been wronged,\" Kane said lightly. His right eye glowed faintly.</p><p>The Priestess raised her nose, \"Insolent ra\u2014\"</p><p>Pandion raised his voice, \"I would be careful to bring up anything offensive at this table amongst all of the other countries. We wouldn\u0027t want to have to question Westria\u0027s dedication to the cause of peace, would we?\"</p><p>Shannon coughed in response to Kane\u0027s comment, \"Yeah I mean... weren\u0027t you the one who suggested Batta to lead the expedition?\"</p><p>Aeriele\u0027s face twisted, \"What an idiotic idea to begin with...\"</p><p>The Bishop stood up from her chair, \"Maybe if the other nations had offered operatives of renown, this wouldn\u0027t have been a problem. If they had offered their BEST. Say what you want about Batta, but she was a hero with many accomplishments. Yet you all send a bunch of no-names.\"</p>","chapter":2}]};
